:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/9190A1FC-F9CE-4B53-AF24-30683B343C1C"><gtr:id>9190A1FC-F9CE-4B53-AF24-30683B343C1C</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>David</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Leach</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=G0401313"><gtr:id>36A573AE-462A-44E1-96EA-8F1548A21338</gtr:id><gtr:title>DNA Misfolding and Maintenance of Genome Stability during Recombination and Repair</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0401313</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>We are trying to find out how cells process DNA sequences that can mis-fold into structures more complex than the normal double-helix.
DNA palindromes are sequences that can mis-fold into hairpin structures that are recognised by a protein that digests mis-folded DNA structures. We hope to understand the consequences of this reaction, which is predicted to generate a broken chromosome. If the chromosome is indeed broken, we will study its repair in a reaction called recombination that uses the genetic information present on another copy of the same chromosome. This analysis is important in the context that long DNA palindromes are sites of chromosomal rearrangements that occur between generations and during the development of cancer. Recombination is important as it is a key mechanism for repairing DNA breaks however they are generated.
Similar analyses will be carried out on repeated DNA sequences such as those implicated in Huntington disease, myotonic dystrophy and fragile-X syndrome.
The work will concentrate on the analysis of events occurring inside cells and will take advantage of new techniques of fluorescence microscopy to visualise events as they occur in living cells.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>DNA misfolding is a threat to genome stability. We propose to investigate the recombination pathways initiated by misfolded DNA, relate these to the instability of the misfoldable sequences themselves and to the processing of covalent cleavage-complexes. In so doing we will test specific hypotheses of recombinational repair. We will also investigate the consequences of recombination for the replication and segregation of chromosomes. To facilitate this work we have manipulated a region of the E. coli chromosome that incorporates two cassettes for monitoring sister-chromatid exchange and two arrays of binding sites for fluorescently labelled proteins flanking a site for insertion for misfoldable DNA. This ?superconstruct? has been designed so that it is portable between organisms and we will use it in E. coli, S. pombe and DT40 cells. The work will be carried out using palindromes and trinucleotide repeats so that clear comparisons can be made between these two types of sequence. We have obtained the first preliminary evidence that trinucleotide repeat sequences can adopt pseudo-cruciform structures in negatively supercoiled DNA using single-molecules in magnetic tweezers. These single-molecule experiments will be pursued and extended to the unwinding of misfolded DNA and reversal of replication forks by helicases.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1049533</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collabor